04533nam a22006495i 9780814768372DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20032003nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147683727 a10.18574/97808147683722doi  a(DE-B1597)547808  a(OCoLC)782878028  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBL65.E75bR47 2003 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a291.1/7834822100aReligion and the Creation of Race and Ethnicity :bAn Introduction /cCraig R. Prentiss. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2003] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion, Race, and Ethnicity ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. "A Servant of Servants Shall He Be" -- tChapter 2. Myth and African American Self-Identity -- tChapter 3. Almost White -- tChapter 4. Indigenous Identity and Story -- tChapter 5. Jew and Judaist, Ethnic and Religious -- tChapter 6. Blackness in the Nation of Islam -- tChapter 7. Theologizing Race -- tChapter 8. "Loathsome unto Thy People" -- tChapter 9. Our Lady of Guadalupe -- tChapter 10. Myths, Shinto, and Matsuri in the Shaping of Japanese Cultural Identity -- tChapter 11. Islam, Arabs, and Ethnicity -- tChapter 12. Cosmic Men and Fluid Exchanges -- tChapter 13. Religious Myth and the Construction of Shona Identity -- tChapter 14. Sacral Ruins in Bosnia-Herzegovina -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligion and the Creation of Race and Ethnicity is the first collection devoted to demonstrating the role that religion and myth have played in the creation of the categories of "race" and "ethnicity." When scholars approach religion and race, they tend to focus on such issues as how African Americans have expressed Christianity, or how Japanese or Mexicans have lived "religiously." This volume, meant specifically for those new to the field, brings together an ensemble of prominent scholars and illuminates instead the role religious myths have played in shaping those very social boundaries that we call "races" and "ethnicities." It asks, what part did Christianity play in creating "Blackness"? To what extent was Japanese or Mexican identity itself the product of religious life?The text, comprised of all original material, introduces readers to the social construction of race and ethnicity and the ways in which these concepts are shaped by religious narratives. It offers examples from both the U.S. and around the world, exploring these themes in the context of places as diverse as Bosnia, India, Japan, Mexico, Zimbabwe, and the Middle East. The volume helps make the case that any account of the social construction of race and ethnicity will be incomplete if it fails to consider the influence of religious traditions and myths. Contributors include: Eddie S. Glaude, Jr., Joel Martin, Jacob Neusner, Roberto S. Goizueta, Laurie Patton, and Michael A. Sells.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aEthnicityxReligious aspects. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aPrentiss, Craig R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814768372423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814768372.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK